{{Refimprove|date=September 2018}}
'''Calx''' is a substance formed from an ore or mineral that has been heated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/calx|title=calx {{!}} Definition of calx in English by Oxford Dictionaries|website=Oxford Dictionaries {{!}} English|access-date=2017-12-28}}</ref>

Calx, especially of a metal, is now known as an [[oxide]]. According to the obsolete [[phlogiston theory]], the calx was the true elemental substance, having lost its phlogiston in the process of [[combustion]]. {{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}

"Calx" is also sometimes used in older texts on artist's techniques to mean [[calcium oxide]]. {{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}

==Etymology==
Calx is Latin for [[chalk]] or [[limestone]], from the Greek χάλιξ (''khaliks'', “pebble”).  It is not to be confused with the Latin [[homonym]] meaning [[heel]]bone (or [[calcaneus]] in modern medical Latin), which has an entirely separate derivation.

==In popular culture==
*[[United Kingdom|UK]] [[electronic music]] artist [[Aphex Twin]] named four of his tracks after differently coloured calxes (green, yellow, blue and red).

