{{wiktionary|creepy|eerie}} {{Other uses|Creepy (disambiguation)}}
'''Creepiness''' is the state of being [[wikt:creepy|creepy]], or causing an unpleasant feeling of [[fear]] or [[wikt:unease|unease]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thesocietypages.org/socimages/2015/12/26/what-is-creepiness/|title=What is “creepiness”? - Sociological Images| |first=The Society|last=Pages|website=thesocietypages.org}}</ref> A person who exhibits creepy behaviour is called a '''creep'''. Certain traits or hobbies may make people seem creepy to others. The internet has been described as increasingly creepy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/cultural-comment/the-age-of-creepiness|title=The Age of Creepiness|website=The New Yorker}}</ref> [[Adam Kotsko]] has compared the modern conception of creepiness to the [[Freudian]] concept of ''[[unheimlich]]''. The term has also been used to describe [[paranormal]] or [[supernatural]] phenomena.
==History and studies== [[File:Clown chili peppers.jpg|thumb|140px||Clowns are thought by some as creepy]] The concept of creepiness has only recently been formally addressed in [[social media marketing]].<ref>Bikramjit Rishi, Subir Bandyopadhyay ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=epcuDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=snippet&q=creepy%20OR%20creepiness&f=false Contemporary Issues in Social Media Marketing]'' 1317193989 2017 "In this chapter, we define creepiness and discuss how privacy and perceived creepiness differ. Then, we explain why creepiness matters and provide recommendations to minimize the negative effect of perceived creepiness on customer ..."</ref> In the abstract the feeling of "creepiness" is subjective: for example some [[dolls]] have been described as creepy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/69472/what-creepiness|title=What is 'Creepiness'?|date=6 October 2015|publisher=}}</ref> Part of the modern attribute of "creepiness" includes the feeling of social stalking and privacy invasions. For example, the practice of [[Real-time ridesharing|ride share]] service [[Uber (company)|Uber]] monitoring the post-ride activity of its passengers has been described as creepy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/tech/2017/08/29/uber-is-getting-rid-creepy-tracking-feature-in-its-app.html|title=Uber is getting rid of a creepy tracking feature in its app|first=Chris|last=Ciaccia|date=29 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref> In 2017 the company announced that they would be ending this practice. An example of purported creepy behavior is that by the purity pledgers of the purity movement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rewire.news/article/2010/11/10/daddy-abstinence-worldtough-women/|title=Daddy I Do: "Purity" World is Tough for Women - Rewire.News|publisher=}}</ref>
==Genderization== A 2016 study by Francis McAndrew and Sara Koehnke from [[Knox College (Illinois)]] surveyed 1,342 people of all ages (1,029 females and 312 male) about what kind of traits the subjects found creepy if a friend was describing meeting someone new to them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sciencealert.com/how-creepy-are-you-scientists-have-published-the-first-definitive-measure-of-creepiness|title=Scientists Have Published The First Definitive Study of Creepiness|first=Fiona|last=MacDonald|publisher=}}</ref> The study found that men were more likely to be seen as creepy than women. Females are more likely than males to perceive sexual threat from a creepy person. Unpredictability is an important component of creepiness. Also hobbies and occupations related to handling the dead, clowns, and [[bird watching]] were commonly thought as creepy. A post on Jezebel has said that there exists a blurriness and ill-defined difference between healthy forms of male sexual expression and being creepy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jezebel.com/5658193/why-do-we-demonize-men-who-are-honest-about-their-sexual-needs|title=Why Do We Demonize Men Who Are Honest About Their Sexual Needs?|first=Clarisse |last=Thorn|publisher=}}</ref> The term ''creep'' is typically applied to unattractive people, a facet that has resulted in some analysts describing the term as cacophobic.<ref>van der Meer, Job, et al. "[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Yanda_Rood/publication/51747607_Prevalence_demographic_and_clinical_characteristics_of_body_dysmorphic_disorder_among_psychiatric_outpatients_with_mood_anxiety_or_somatoform_disorders/links/0c96053c4d469a57a3000000/Prevalence-demographic-and-clinical-characteristics-of-body-dysmorphic-disorder-among-psychiatric-outpatients-with-mood-anxiety-or-somatoform-disorders.pdf Prevalence, demographic and clinical characteristics of body dysmorphic disorder among psychiatric outpatients with mood, anxiety or somatoform disorders]." Nordic journal of psychiatry 66.4 (2012): 232-238</ref>
