{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}} {{Infobox NRHP |name= Lewis and Clark Trail–Travois Road |nrhp_type= |image= Travois Trail To Blue Mountains - Plowed field is the trail from the West.jpg |caption= Trail in the foreground |image_size= 280 |location= {{convert|5|mi}} east of Pomeroy on [[U.S. Route 12 in Washington|US&nbsp;12]] |nearest_city= [[Pomeroy, Washington]] |coordinates = {{coord|46|27|52|N|117|28|23|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Washington#USA | map_label = {{PAGENAME}} |built= |builder= |architecture= |added= January 11, 1974 |area= {{convert|5|acre}} |governing_body= Private |refnum= 74001952<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }}
The '''Lewis and Clark Trail–Travois Road''' is a {{convert|5|acre|adj=on}} historic site located {{convert|5|mi|km}} east of [[Pomeroy, Washington]], on [[U.S. Route 12 in Washington|U.S. Route 12]] (US&nbsp;12). It is a surviving stretch of Indian [[travois]] trail followed by [[Lewis and Clark Expedition|Lewis and Clark]] in their 1805–06 expedition and mentioned in their writings. It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1974.<ref name=nris/><ref name=nrhpdoc>{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=74001952}} |title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory/Nomination: Lewis and Clark Trail–Travois Road |author= |date= |publisher=National Park Service}} and {{NRHP url|id=74001952|title=accompanying photos|photos=y}}</ref>
The site is significant for the 1805–06 event, for including "a trail that was very important in aboriginal times", and for its information potential.<ref name=nrhpdoc/> It seems to have been described by [[Meriwether Lewis]], who wrote on May 3, 1806: "...we Continued Still up the Creek bottoms ... to the place at which the roade leaves the [Pataha] Creek and assends the hill up to the high plains: here we Encamped in a Small grove of Cotton trees...".<ref name=expedition>{{cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/lewisandclark/lew.htm |title=Lewis & Clark Trail–Travois Road |work=Lewis and Clark Expedition: A National Register of Historic Places Travel Itinerary |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=October 24, 2013}}</ref>
Travois were used by [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indians]] to transport possessions by means of two long poles slung with a hammock trailing behind a horse or dog. The deep, parallel tracks caused by the dragging poles are still visible today in a quarter-mile (0.4&nbsp;km) section of the original trail, sometimes called the [[Nez Perce Trail]], followed by the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] and preserved at this site.<ref name=expedition/>
