{{Infobox person | name = Nikolai Grigoryevich Cholodny | image = Nikolai Cholodny.jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 22 June 1882 | birth_place = [[Tambov]], [[Russian Empire]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1953|05|04|1882|06|22|df=y}} | death_place = [[Kiev]], [[USSR]] | nationality = USSR | other_names = | known_for = [[Cholodny–Went model]] | occupation = Microbiologist }} '''Nikolai Grigoryevich Cholodny''' ({{lang-ru|Никола́й Григо́рьевич Холо́дный }}; 22 June 1882 – 4 May 1953) was an influential microbiologist who worked at the [[University of Kiev]], [[Ukrainian SSR|Ukraine]] in the [[USSR]] during the 1930s.
He is known for the [[Cholodny–Went model]], which he developed independently with [[Frits Warmolt Went]] of the [[California Institute of Technology]]. Despite being associated with the same theory, the two men never actually met.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/pdf/10.1146/annurev.pp.25.060174.000245 |title=Reflections and Speculations |author=F.W, Went |year=1974 |journal=Annual Review of Plant Physiology |accessdate=2012-06-17 |doi=10.1146/annurev.pp.25.060174.000245 |volume=25 |pages=1–27}}</ref>
Cholodny worked in the [[A.V. Fomin Botanical Garden]], attached to the University of Kiev.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fominbotsad.narod.ru/index1.html |title=About Botanical Garden |publisher=O.V. Fomin Botanical Garden |accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref> He was one of the pioneers of the concept that microbes adhere to surfaces, using the technique of first placing glass slides in earth for a measured time period, then using a microscope to examine the slides.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://plato.acadiau.ca/isme/Symposium03/lappin-scott.PDF |title=Claude E. Zobell – his life and contributions to biofilm microbiology |author=Hilary M. Lappin-Scott |year=1999 |work=Proceedings of the 8th International Symposium on Microbial Ecology |accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrcresearchpress.com/doi/abs/10.1139/w01-052 |work=Canadian Journal of Microbiology |year=2001 |volume=47 | issue = 7 |pages=601–607 |title=Adequacy of in situ glass slides and direct sand extractions to assess the microbiota within sand columns used for drinking water treatment |author1=Jonas Långmark |author2=Nicholas J Ashbolt |author3=Ulrich Szewzyk |author4=Thor Axel Stenström |accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref> The [[Prokaryote]] ''Leptothrix cholodnii'' is named after him.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.bacterio.cict.fr/l/leptothrix.html |author = J.P. Euzéby |title = List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature - Genus Leptothrix |accessdate = 2012-06-17 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120302180528/http://www.bacterio.cict.fr/l/leptothrix.html |archivedate = 2012-03-02 |df = }}</ref> In 1927 Cholodny proposed that the cells of the [[coleoptile]] are first polarized under the influence of uneven exposure to light, so growth hormone can diffuse more rapidly towards the side in the shade than in any other direction.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universalis.fr/encyclopedie/tropismes-vegetaux/1-le-phototropisme/ |title=Le phototropisme • Chez les végétaux supérieurs |work=Encyclopædia Universalis France S.A |accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref> Went reached the same conclusion in 1928, and the two scientists' names have been attached to the controversial Cholodny-Went theory.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.plantphysiol.org/content/103/1/157.full.pdf |journal=Plant Physiology |year=1993 |volume=103 |pages=157–163 |title=Growth Distribution during Phototropism of Arabidopsis thaliana Seedlings |author1=Vladimir Orbovik |author2=Kenneth I. Poff |lastauthoramp=yes |accessdate=2012-06-17 |issue=1 |doi=10.1104/pp.103.1.157|pmc=158958}}</ref>
==Bibliography==
Selected works include:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldcat.org/identities/viaf-54544196 |title=Cholodny, N. |work=Worldcat |accessdate=2012-06-17}}</ref> *1926 ''Die eisenbakterien : bieträge zu einer monographie'' by N Cholodny *1928 ''Über eine vermeintliche Anomalie im Wachstumsmodus der Wurzeln von Lupinus albus'' by N Cholodny *1932 ''Lichtwachstumsreaktion und Phototropismus 2'' by N Cholodny *1933 ''Zum Problem der Bildung und physiologischen Wirkung des Wuchshormons bei den Wurzeln'' by N Cholodny *1939 ''Spezielle Methoden''.
In 1937 N. G. Cholodny and E. Ch. Sankewitsch published an article on ''Influence of weak electric currents upon the growth of the coleoptile'' in ''[[Plant Physiology (journal)|Plant Physiology]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Plant Physiology |date=April 1937 |volume=12 |pages=385–408 |title=Influence of weak electric currents upon the growth of the coleoptile |author1=N. G. Cholodny |author2=E. Ch. Sankewitsch |lastauthoramp=yes |pmc=439299 |pmid=16653418 |issue=2 |doi=10.1104/pp.12.2.385}}</ref> The same year he published an article on ''Charles Darwin and the modern theory of tropisms'' in ''Science'' magazine.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/86/2238/468.1.full.pdf?sid=ac8eadfa-8705-493e-97f7-4ba92c7cc405 |title=Charles Darwin and the modern theory of tropisms |author=Cholodny |journal=Science |date=19 November 1937|page= 468 | volume=86 |DOI=10.1126/science.86.2238.468 |accessdate=2012-06-17 |issue=2238 |pmid=17815459}}</ref>
